aps a variant of   Mearns   with loss of final <i>-s</i> or else possibly a variant of   Morrin   1.","Slovenian: nickname from an old spelling of the archaic adjective <i>maren</i> meaning ‘diligent’, but also ‘worthless’. Compare   Maren  ."]}]},{"name":"Jean","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Like   Jane   and   Joan  , a medieval variant of Old French <i>Je(h)anne</i>. Towards the end of the Middle Ages this form became largely confined to Scotland. In the 20th century it became more widely used in the English-speaking world and enjoyed a period of great popularity, but it is now out of fashion. Among numerous well-known and influential bearers are the British novelists  Jean Plaidy  (  Eleanor Hibbert ,  1910–93 ) and  Jean Rhys  (  Ella Gwendolen Rees Williams ,  1894–1979 ), British actress  Jean Simmons  (  1929–2010 ), and American-born actress  Jean Seberg  (  1938–79 ). It is also found as a variant spelling of the masculine name   Gene ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["Greek: the Lord gave graciously; whom Jehovah gave; whom Jehovah bestowed."]},{"name":"Jeane","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Jean ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Countess Jean of Mearns was born about 1100, in Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland. She had at least 1 son with Reinald McGaughan. She died in 1187, in her hometown, at the age of 88."},"et":{"about 1100–1187":"umbes 1100–1187","1095–1127":"1095–1127","1124–1204":"1124–1204","1100–1187":"1100–1187","1204":"1204","1127":"1127","1124":"1124","about 1127":"umbes 1127","1100":"1100","1187":"1187","1095":"1095","about 1100":"umbes 1100","Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland":"Newton Mearns, Renfrewshire, Scotland"},"fi":{"about 1100–1187":"noin 1100–1187","1095–1127":"1095–1127","1124–1204":"1124–1204","1100–1187":"1100–1187","1204":"1204","1127":"1127","1124":"1124","about 1127":"noin 1127","1100":"1100","1187":"1187","1095":"1095","about 